00:11:35,375 --> 00:11:37,708
[phone ringing]

245
00:11:37,791 --> 00:11:39,083
[TSUKASA]
Hiiragi residence.

246
00:11:39,166 --> 00:11:40,708
[KONATA]
Uh, Tsukasa.

247
00:11:40,791 --> 00:11:42,375
[TSUKASA]
Kona-chan?

248
00:11:42,458 --> 00:11:43,958
It's so early. Anything wrong?

249
00:11:44,041 --> 00:11:45,916
[KONATA]
Yeah, it's the curry.

250
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:47,666
[TSUKASA]
Curry?

251
00:11:47,750 --> 00:11:49,083
[KONATA]
The curry I made yesterday,

252
00:11:49,166 --> 00:11:51,500
I left it out overnight,
and it spoiled.

253
00:11:51,583 --> 00:11:52,791
[TSUKASA]
What? No way.

254
00:11:52,875 --> 00:11:54,625
[KONATA]
Way.

255
00:11:54,708 --> 00:11:57,250
[TSUKASA] But why? Curry doesn't
usually go bad overnight.

256
00:11:57,333 --> 00:11:58,500
[KONATA] I
know.

257
00:11:58,583 --> 00:12:00,041
[TSUKASA] Did you put
something weird in it?

258
00:12:00,125 --> 00:12:01,833
[KONATA]
No, but this morning there

259
00:12:01,916 --> 00:12:03,125
was mold all over it.

260
00:12:03,208 --> 00:12:05,250
So cornets for lunch again?

261
00:12:05,333 --> 00:12:07,083
I don't mind.
This thing's tasty.

262
00:12:07,166 --> 00:12:08,625
Well, as long as
you're okay with it.

263
00:12:08,708 --> 00:12:10,708
Wait, hang on a second.

264
00:12:10,791 --> 00:12:12,500
You know, I just
realized something

265
00:12:12,583 --> 00:12:15,000
about the kind of lunches
you guys bring to school.

266
00:12:15,083 --> 00:12:16,958
Some days you bring
proper lunches,

267
00:12:17,041 --> 00:12:19,000
and other days you
bring simple lunches.

268
00:12:19,083 --> 00:12:20,875
Why's there such
a huge difference?

269
00:12:20,958 --> 00:12:23,541
Oh, well, that's because
Tsukasa and I always take

270
00:12:23,625 --> 00:12:25,166
turns making the lunches.

271
00:12:25,250 --> 00:12:26,583
Hmm.

272
00:12:26,666 --> 00:12:28,458
Stuff like lunches always
end up being kinda simple

273
00:12:28,541 --> 00:12:30,750
'cause I'm not that good
at doing housework.

274
00:12:30,833 --> 00:12:32,541
There, I'm simple.
Happy now?

275
00:12:32,625 --> 00:12:35,166
Yes! Kagami, you're the
type of person who makes pots

276
00:12:35,250 --> 00:12:37,041
and pans explode
whenever you cook.

277
00:12:37,125 --> 00:12:38,833
Relax, nobody can do that.

278
00:12:38,916 --> 00:12:42,541
Wow, Yuki-chan, your lunch
looks super tasty today.

279
00:12:42,625 --> 00:12:44,708
[MIYUKI]
Really? Oh, I just packed

280
00:12:44,791 --> 00:12:46,916
some of last night's leftovers.

281
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,708
[GROUP]
Oh!

282
00:12:48,791 --> 00:12:50,458
[KONATA]
Dinner at Mikyuki-san's house.

283
00:12:50,541 --> 00:12:51,958
[TSUKASA]
Is really fancy.

284
00:12:52,041 --> 00:12:54,291
[KAGAMI] And these
are just the leftovers.

285
00:12:54,375 --> 00:12:56,541
Hey, um, everything
looks so good,

286
00:12:56,625 --> 00:12:58,833
what's the filling
inside the fried eggs?

287
00:12:58,916 --> 00:13:01,208
[MIYUKI]
Oh, well, we had eel last night,

288
00:13:01,291 --> 00:13:04,291
so I just put that
into the eggs.

289
00:13:04,375 --> 00:13:06,500
[TSUKASA]
You never see leftover eel.

290
00:13:06,583 --> 00:13:09,666
[KONATA] Moldy curry's
the only leftover at my house.

291
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:12,541
[KAGAMI] Well, your house
isn't really normal, is it?

292
00:13:12,625 --> 00:13:14,666
--Good Morning.
--Hi.

293
00:13:14,750 --> 00:13:16,333
Hey, you.

294
00:13:16,416 --> 00:13:19,375
Look, look, my parents
bought me a cell phone.

295
00:13:19,458 --> 00:13:21,125
That's pretty cool of them.

296
00:13:21,208 --> 00:13:23,708
Yeah, I did really good
on my exams this time,

297
00:13:23,791 --> 00:13:25,000
so they got it for me.

298
00:13:25,083 --> 00:13:26,500
Well, now that you
finally got one,

299
00:13:26,583 --> 00:13:28,166
give me your number
and I'll give you mine.

300
00:13:28,250 --> 00:13:31,916
Sure, I just gotta
go find my number.

301
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:33,208
Let's see.

302
00:13:33,291 --> 00:13:35,250
[beeping]

303
00:13:38,375 --> 00:13:39,333
Hmm.

304
00:13:39,416 --> 00:13:42,166
[beeping]

305
00:13:42,250 --> 00:13:47,000
Uh, sorry,
this'll take a second.

306
00:13:50,791 --> 00:13:53,500
Oh, oh!

307
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:56,041
[beeping]

308
00:14:00,916 --> 00:14:04,125
I didn't know you had
a cell phone, Konata.

309
00:14:04,208 --> 00:14:07,208
Except I keep it at home 'cause
I always forget to bring it.

310
00:14:07,291 --> 00:14:09,541
Besides, my dad's the only
one who ever calls me.

311
00:14:09,625 --> 00:14:12,250
Then it's pointless for you
to even have a cell phone.

312
00:14:12,333 --> 00:14:13,250
Oh, yeah?

313
00:14:13,333 --> 00:14:14,958
--Kerororo.
--Whoa!

314
00:14:15,041 --> 00:14:17,041
Isn't he cute?
Mom and Dad bought him for me

315
00:14:17,125 --> 00:14:18,708
with the cell phone.

316
00:14:18,791 --> 00:14:21,000
That reminds me,
there's this girl in my class

317
00:14:21,083 --> 00:14:23,500
who's got a ton of straps
hanging from her phone.

318
00:14:23,583 --> 00:14:25,625
She decided to weigh it
to see how heavy it was,

319
00:14:25,708 --> 00:14:27,916
and the straps alone
were like 800 grams.

320
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:29,833
Oh, wow, that's a lot.

321
00:14:29,916 --> 00:14:31,125
That's heavy.

322
00:14:31,208 --> 00:14:32,458
Once she took the straps off,

323
00:14:32,541 --> 00:14:34,000
her shoulders didn't hurt
anymore.

324
00:14:34,083 --> 00:14:35,750
Think about it,
every time she made a call

325
00:14:35,833 --> 00:14:38,875
or answered the phone
she was working out.

326
00:14:38,958 --> 00:14:41,291
It's weird, but cell phones
always make me nervous,

327
00:14:41,375 --> 00:14:43,458
you never really know know
when they're gonna ring.

328
00:14:43,541 --> 00:14:44,833
Really.

329
00:14:44,916 --> 00:14:46,791
Oh, I hope somebody calls me
on my new cell phone.

330
00:14:46,875 --> 00:14:48,750
You're losing it
over a cell phone.

331
00:14:48,833 --> 00:14:50,250
These days they're
not that big a deal.

332
00:14:50,333 --> 00:14:51,750
[giggles]

333
00:14:51,833 --> 00:14:53,500
By the way,
did you ever find your number?

334
00:14:53,583 --> 00:14:55,791
Oh! Oh, not yet.

335
00:14:55,875 --> 00:14:57,750
[NANAKO] And in England,
the House of Lancaster and

336
00:14:57,833 --> 00:15:00,666
the House of York began a series
of civil wars for the throne.

337
00:15:00,750 --> 00:15:03,791
On the battlefield, the armies
of Lancaster wore red roses,

338
00:15:03,875 --> 00:15:05,500
and the armies
of York wore white.

339
00:15:05,583 --> 00:15:07,750
That's why it's called
the War of the Roses.

340
00:15:07,833 --> 00:15:10,875
The fighting started
in 1455 and went all the way

341
00:15:10,958 --> 00:15:12,000
to 1485 and that's when--

342
00:15:12,083 --> 00:15:13,583
[music playing]

343
00:15:13,666 --> 00:15:17,750
[gasps] Uh, what is that?
Is that my cell phone?

344
00:15:17,833 --> 00:15:20,416
Oh, I finally got a call.

345
00:15:23,875 --> 00:15:28,083
[sighs] Huh? Who's this?

346
00:15:28,166 --> 00:15:31,333
Okay, confiscated.

347
00:15:31,416 --> 00:15:33,958
You can pick it up at
my office after school.

348
00:15:34,041 --> 00:15:36,625
Yay! She gave it back to me.

349
00:15:36,708 --> 00:15:39,458
It sucks that your first
call was a spam text.

350
00:15:39,541 --> 00:15:42,000
[phone vibrating]

351
00:15:42,083 --> 00:15:46,333
Hi, oh, hey, Dad,
yeah I'm still at school.

352
00:15:46,416 --> 00:15:48,000
Just hanging out
with Konata and Miyuki

353
00:15:48,083 --> 00:15:50,750
and lost track of time.
Yeah, I'm fine.

354
00:15:50,833 --> 00:15:54,541
I'll be heading home in
a little bit. See ya.

355
00:15:54,625 --> 00:15:56,916
That always happens even
if I'm a little late.

356
00:15:57,000 --> 00:15:59,791
--[laughs]
--[music plays]

357
00:15:59,875 --> 00:16:04,583
Hello? Oh, hiya, Dad,
yeah, I'm still at school

358
00:16:04,666 --> 00:16:07,833
with Kona-chan
and the others, yeah.

359
00:16:07,916 --> 00:16:10,625
You think he'd figure it out
after calling one of us.

360
00:16:10,708 --> 00:16:12,375
Fathers always worry
about their daughters,

361
00:16:12,458 --> 00:16:13,916
it's what they do best.

362
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:18,500
[phone ringing]

363
00:16:18,583 --> 00:16:21,416
[KAGAMI] Can you believe how
much spam you get these days?

364
00:16:21,500 --> 00:16:23,083
[KONATA] You just need
to change your address

365
00:16:23,166 --> 00:16:24,916
to something that's
not too obvious.

366
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:27,166
I changed mine,
and it's all good.

367
00:16:27,250 --> 00:16:29,916
Not too obvious, huh?
Gimme an example.

368
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:31,916
Well, I got my address
written out to say

369
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:34,083
"meganekko geki love" in romaji.

370
00:16:34,166 --> 00:16:36,625
What I really wanted was
something with maid in it,

371
00:16:36,708 --> 00:16:39,666
but addresses with maid-san
and miko-san are so popular

372
00:16:39,750 --> 00:16:41,000
they've all been snapped up.

373
00:16:41,083 --> 00:16:42,916
Wait, you don't
have to broadcast it

374
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,166
to everyone on the bus.
I got it, I got it already.

375
00:16:45,250 --> 00:16:47,958
The stuff you're talking about
is worse than the spam problem.

376
00:16:48,041 --> 00:16:50,833
[phone rings]

377
00:16:50,916 --> 00:16:52,875
Good morning!

378
00:16:52,958 --> 00:16:54,250
Hey, you.

379
00:16:54,333 --> 00:16:55,791
[TSUKASA crying]

380
00:16:55,875 --> 00:16:58,833
Oh, why are you crying?
What's wrong?

381
00:16:58,916 --> 00:17:02,208
[cries] My poor little cell
phone, it never hurt anyone.

382
00:17:02,291 --> 00:17:05,333
She sort of forgot
to take it out of her pocket.

383
00:17:05,416 --> 00:17:08,208
Aw, then it's gone on
to a much better place.

384
00:17:08,291 --> 00:17:10,250
[wailing]

385
00:17:10,333 --> 00:17:13,458
They'll never buy me
another cell phone again.

386
00:17:13,541 --> 00:17:16,833
Oh, he made it
through unscathed.

387
00:17:16,916 --> 00:17:19,875
Persistent little guy.

388
00:17:19,958 --> 00:17:22,708
Oh, hey, about that text
you sent me last night.

389
00:17:22,791 --> 00:17:25,166
You know the one that said
something about how Kagami

390
00:17:25,250 --> 00:17:27,875
wanted me to return her
homework notes today?

391
00:17:27,958 --> 00:17:29,500
Was that the last
message you sent?

392
00:17:29,583 --> 00:17:31,833
Yeah, that was the
last, did you reply to it?

393
00:17:31,916 --> 00:17:33,291
Huh? Let's see.

394
00:17:33,375 --> 00:17:34,708
How come it's so hard for you

395
00:17:34,791 --> 00:17:36,791
to return a simple
text message?!

396
00:17:36,875 --> 00:17:38,500
I never reply to a text
when it's from someone

397
00:17:38,583 --> 00:17:40,083
I'll be talking to later on.

398
00:17:40,166 --> 00:17:42,083
You're supposed
to reply to those things.

399
00:17:42,166 --> 00:17:44,625
I see you every day. What's the
point in going to that trouble?

400
00:17:44,708 --> 00:17:46,458
You're gonna lose
friends that way.

401
00:17:46,541 --> 00:17:48,875
Ah, it's not like it's
so important it can't wait.

402
00:17:48,958 --> 00:17:50,208
How can you say that?

403
00:17:50,291 --> 00:17:52,333
[cicadas chirping]

404
00:17:52,416 --> 00:17:54,541
Huh, after all
the back and forth,

405
00:17:54,625 --> 00:17:57,250
I still didn't
get my notes back.

406
00:17:57,333 --> 00:18:00,250
[car horns honk]

407
00:18:03,708 --> 00:18:06,208
[KAGAMI]
Tsukasa, can I come in?

408
00:18:06,291 --> 00:18:08,375
--Oh, hey, sis.
--Ha!

409
00:18:08,458 --> 00:18:09,958
--[laughs]
--What's wrong?

410
00:18:10,041 --> 00:18:11,708
Why are you crying?

411
00:18:11,791 --> 00:18:15,208
This manga I borrowed
from Kona-chan made me weepy.

412
00:18:15,291 --> 00:18:17,833
Good morning! Thanks
for letting me borrow the manga.

413
00:18:17,916 --> 00:18:19,458
It was really cool.

414
00:18:19,541 --> 00:18:21,583
Yeah, wasn't that silly,
bet it made ya laugh.

415
00:18:21,666 --> 00:18:25,416
Huh? But it was so touching
that it made me cry.

416
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:26,666
It's hard to believe you guys

417
00:18:26,750 --> 00:18:28,375
are talking about
the same manga.

418
00:18:28,458 --> 00:18:30,333
Here if you cry,
you're on Tsukasa's side,

419
00:18:30,416 --> 00:18:32,500
but if you laugh,
you're on my side.

420
00:18:32,583 --> 00:18:33,916
No way.

421
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:35,666
I don't wanna be classified
with either one of you.

422
00:18:35,750 --> 00:18:38,708
I think it'd be kinda neat
to see how you react to it.

423
00:18:38,791 --> 00:18:40,416
Oh, is it really
such a bad thing to

424
00:18:40,500 --> 00:18:43,333
wanna know what your
friends are all about?.

